{"questionId":"21944442","questionHtml":"<p>Find the area of the triangle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>UVW</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong></p>\n<p>triangle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>UVW</mi></math> has height <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math> and base <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempt to find area of triangle with their height and base&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>(M1)</em></strong></p>\n<p>area <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>×</mo><mn>3</mn></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></math> (square units)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2</strong></p>\n<p>triangle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>UVW</mi></math> has sides of length&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msqrt><msup><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mfenced><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><msqrt><mn>12</mn></msqrt></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempt to find area of equilateral triangle with their side length&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>area&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mfenced><msqrt><mn>12</mn></msqrt></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;OR&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msqrt><mn>12</mn></msqrt><mfenced><mn>3</mn></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;OR&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced><msqrt><mn>12</mn></msqrt></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>×</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></math>&nbsp;(square units)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 3</strong></p>\n<p>triangle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>UVO</mi></math> has sides of length&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msqrt><msup><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mfenced><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempt to find area of three isosceles triangles with their side length and angle&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>area&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></math>&nbsp;(square units)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"21944442","referenc